{
  "chapter_number": 15,
  "chapter_title": "Enumerations (enum) and typedef",
  "sections": [
    {
      "section_title": "Introduction",
      "keywords": ["enum", "typedef"],
      "content": "Enumerations and typedef are user-defined data type features in C that improve code readability and maintainability."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "What is Enumeration?",
      "keywords": ["enum definition"],
      "content": "An enumeration is a user-defined data type consisting of a set of named integer constants."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Syntax of enum",
      "keywords": ["enum syntax"],
      "content": "enum Day {SUN, MON, TUE, WED, THU, FRI, SAT};"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Default Values in enum",
      "keywords": ["enum values"],
      "content": "By default, the first enumeration constant has value 0 and subsequent constants increase by 1."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Custom Values in enum",
      "keywords": ["custom enum"],
      "content": "Enumeration constants can be assigned custom integer values."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Advantages of enum",
      "keywords": ["enum advantages"],
      "content": [
        "Improves readability",
        "Reduces use of magic numbers",
        "Makes code easier to maintain"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "What is typedef?",
      "keywords": ["typedef definition"],
      "content": "typedef is a keyword used to create an alias name for an existing data type."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Syntax of typedef",
      "keywords": ["typedef syntax"],
      "content": "typedef int Integer;"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "typedef with Structures",
      "keywords": ["typedef structure"],
      "content": "typedef can simplify structure declarations."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Advantages of typedef",
      "keywords": ["typedef advantages"],
      "content": [
        "Simplifies declarations",
        "Improves readability",
        "Makes code easier to maintain"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Difference Between enum and typedef",
      "keywords": ["comparison"],
      "content": [
        "enum creates named constants.",
        "typedef creates aliases for data types."
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Applications",
      "keywords": ["applications"],
      "content": [
        "Menu Systems",
        "State Management",
        "Readable Code",
        "Large Software Projects"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Example Program",
      "keywords": ["example"],
      "content": "#include <stdio.h>\n\nenum Day {SUN, MON, TUE};\n\nint main()\n{\n enum Day today = MON;\n printf(\"%d\", today);\n return 0;\n}"
    }
  ],
  "summary": [
    "enum creates named constants.",
    "The first enum value is 0 by default.",
    "typedef creates aliases for existing data types.",
    "Both improve code readability."
  ]
}
